5. Make a barplot where you show the previous results - average CO2 emissions per capita across continents in 1960 and 2016. 

# Filter data for 1960 and 2016
data_filtered <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(time %in% c(1960, 2016)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(region))

avg_co2_PC <- data_filtered %>% 
  group_by(time, region) %>% 
  summarise(avg_co2_PC = mean(co2_PC, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(avg_co2_PC, aes(x = region, y = avg_co2_PC, fill = factor(time))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Continent", y = "Average CO2 Emissions", 
       title = "Average CO2 Emissions by Continent in 1960 and 2016") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#1f78b4", "#a6cee3"), 
                    name = "Year", labels = c("1960", "2016"))

GDP per capita

1. Make a scatterplot of GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country, using data for 1960. Make the point size dependent on the country size, and color those according to the continent. Comment what you see there.

data_1960 <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(time == 1960 &(!is.na(region)))

ggplot(data_1960, aes(x = GDP_PC, y = lifeExpectancy)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = totalPopulation, color = region)) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(1,10), breaks = c(1e6, 5e7, 1e9), labels = c("1M", "50M", "1B")) +
  labs(title = "GDP per capita vs. Life Expectancy (1960)",
       x = "GDP per capita",
       y = "Life Expectancy",
       size = "Population",
       color = "Continent") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 124 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

In 1960, Europe had on average the highest GDP per capita, and the highest life expectancy. Close behind is the Americas, with similar life expectancy but lower GDP per capita. Oceania has high GDP per capita and a high life expectancy. Asia, with large populations, has very low GDP per capita and life expectancy. Africa has (on average) the lowest life expectancy and GDP per capita.

7. What was the ranking of US in terms of life expectancy in 1960 and in 2019? (When counting from top.) 

life_exp_df <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(time %in% c(1960, 2019)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(region)) %>% 
  select(name, time, lifeExpectancy)

ranked_df <- life_exp_df %>% 
  group_by(time) %>% 
  mutate(rank = rank(-lifeExpectancy))

us_df <- ranked_df %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America")

cat("Rank of US in 1960:", us_df$rank[us_df$time == 1960], "\n")
## Rank of US in 1960: 17
cat("Rank of US in 2019:", us_df$rank[us_df$time == 2019], "\n")
## Rank of US in 2019: 46

8. If you did this correctly, then you noticed that US ranking has been falling quite a bit. But we also have more countries in 2019what about the relative rank divided by the corresponding number of countries that have LE data in the corresponding year?

life_exp_df <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(time %in% c(1960, 2019)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(region)) %>% 
  select(name, time, lifeExpectancy)

n_countries <- life_exp_df %>% 
  group_by(time) %>% 
  summarize(n_countries = n())

life_exp_df <- life_exp_df %>% 
  left_join(n_countries)
## Joining, by = "time"
ranked_df <- life_exp_df %>% 
  group_by(time) %>% 
  mutate(rank = rank(-lifeExpectancy))

us_df <- ranked_df %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America")

relative_rank <- us_df %>% 
  mutate(relative_rank = rank / n_countries)

cat("Relative rank of US in 1960:", relative_rank$relative_rank[relative_rank$time == 1960], "\n")
## Relative rank of US in 1960: 0.08018868
cat("Relative rank of US in 2019:", relative_rank$relative_rank[relative_rank$time == 2019], "\n")
## Relative rank of US in 2019: 0.2159624
